{"title_page": "WNEO", "text_new": "{{short description|PBS member station in Alliance, Ohio}}\n{{for|the WEAO radio station in Columbus, Ohio|WOSU (AM)}}\n{{Infobox broadcast\n| call_letters             = WNEO\n| city                     = Alliance, Ohio\n| station_logo             = Western Reserve PBS logo (2019).png\n| station_branding         = PBS Western Reserve\n| station_slogan           = \n| digital                  = 29 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]])\n| virtual                  = 45 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n| subchannels              = \n| other_chs                = \n| affiliations             = '''45.1:''' [[PBS]]<br>'''45.2:''' Fusion<br>'''45.3:''' [[First Nations Experience|FNX]] \n| owner                    = Western Reserve Public Media\n| licensee                 = Northeastern Educational Television of Ohio, Inc.\n| location                 = [[Alliance, Ohio|Alliance]]/[[Youngstown, Ohio]]\n| country                  = United States\n| airdate                  = {{start date and age|1973|05|30|p=y}}\n| enddate                  = \n| callsign_meaning         = '''N'''orth '''E'''astern '''O'''hio\n| sister_stations          = \n| former_callsigns         = \n| former_channel_numbers   = '''Analog:'''<br>45 (UHF, 1973\u20132008)<br>'''Digital:'''<br>46 (UHF, 2003\u20132008)\n| former_affiliations      = \n| effective_radiated_power = 500 [[kilowatt|kW]]<br>365 kW ([[construction permit|CP]])\n| HAAT                     = {{convert|253|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}<br>{{convert|251.1|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} (CP)\n| facility_id              = 49439\n| coordinates              = {{coord|40|54|23.2|N|80|54|39.3|W|type:landmark_scale:2000}}\n| licensing_authority      = [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]]\n| homepage                 = {{URL|https://westernreservepublicmedia.org/}}\n}}\n{{Infobox broadcast\n| call_letters             = WEAO<br>''([[Broadcast relay station#Satellite stations|satellite]] of WNEO)''\n| city                     = Akron, Ohio\n| station_logo             = \n| station_branding         = see WNEO infobox\n| station_slogan           = \n| digital                  = 24 (UHF)<br>''(shared with [[WRLM (TV)|WRLM]])''\n| virtual                  = 49 (PSIP)\n| subchannels              = \n| other_chs                = \n| affiliations             = '''49.1:''' PBS<br>'''49.2:''' Fusion<br>'''49.3:''' FNX \n| owner                    = Western Reserve Public Media\n| licensee                 = Northeastern Educational Television of Ohio, Inc.\n| location                 = [[Akron, Ohio|Akron]]/[[Canton, Ohio]]\n| country                  = United States\n| airdate                  = {{start date and age|1975|09|21|p=y}}\n| enddate                  = \n| callsign_meaning         = '''EA'''stern '''O'''hio\n| sister_stations          = \n| former_callsigns         = \n| former_channel_numbers   = '''Analog:'''<br>49 (UHF, 1975\u20132009)<br>'''Digital:'''<br>50 (UHF, 2004\u20132019)\n| former_affiliations      = \n| effective_radiated_power = 550 kW ([[special temporary authority|STA]])<br>191 kW ([[construction permit|CP]])\n| HAAT                     = {{convert|215.5|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} (STA)<br>{{convert|293.6|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} (CP)\n| facility_id              = 49421\n| coordinates              = {{coord|41|4|58|N|81|38|1|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|name=WEAO}}\n| licensing_authority      = FCC\n| homepage                 = \n}}\n'''WNEO''', [[virtual channel|virtual]] and [[ultra high frequency|UHF]] [[digital terrestrial television|digital]] channel 29, is a Public Broadcasting Service ([[PBS]]) [[Network affiliate#Member stations|member]] [[television station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Alliance, Ohio]], United States. The station's programming is [[simulcast]] on full-time [[Broadcast relay station#Satellite stations|satellite]] '''WEAO''' (virtual channel 49, UHF digital channel 24) in [[Akron, Ohio|Akron]]. The two stations utilize the unified brand '''PBS Western Reserve'''. WNEO is the PBS member station of record for the [[Youngstown, Ohio|Youngstown]] [[media market|market]], while WEAO provides the [[Cleveland]] market with a second choice for PBS programming alongside the market's primary PBS station, [[WVIZ]] (channel 25).\n\nWNEO and WEAO are owned by Northeastern Educational Television of Ohio, which is a consortium of the [[University of Akron]], [[Kent State University]] and [[Youngstown State University]]. The two stations operate from studios on Kent State's campus in [[Kent, Ohio|Kent]],<ref>{{cite web | title= Organization Profile| url= http://westernreservepublicmedia.org/FACTS.HTM?b1b7cb08| work= WesternReservePublicMedia.org| publisher= Western Reserve Public Media| year= 2009|quote= ''The operations center, administrative offices, main studio and location of public files are housed at 1750 Campus Center Drive, Kent, Ohio, 44240. The organization\u2019s Western Reserve Production Hub is located on the first floor of the United Building in downtown Akron.''| accessdate=21 May 2009}}</ref> northeast of Akron and roughly west of Youngstown. WNEO's transmitter is located in [[Salem, Ohio|Salem]], while WEAO's transmitter is based in [[Copley Township, Summit County, Ohio|Copley Township]].\n\nWNEO also operates '''W44CR-D''', a [[low-power broadcasting#Television|low-power]] digital [[Broadcast relay station#Broadcast translators|translator]] in Youngstown, which serves low-lying areas in the [[Mahoning Valley]] that are not covered from the main WNEO signal. The digital translator, which signed on the air in 2009, is a conversion of a former [[analog television|analog]] translator, W58AM, which broadcast at the same location.<ref>[http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/tvq?call=W44CR-D FCC TV query for W44CR-D]</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Wneo Weao.PNG|115px|thumb|left|WNEO/WEAO's former logo as \"PBS 45 & 49\".]]\n[[File:Wneo weao wr.png|115px|thumb|left|First WNEO/WEAO logo as \"Western Reserve PBS\"; used until November 4, 2019.]]\nWNEO first signed on the air on May 30, 1973. It was originally intended to serve all of northeast Ohio from Youngstown to Cleveland. Its city of license, Alliance, is split between both major markets in the region. Most of the city is in [[Stark County, Ohio|Stark County]], which is in the Cleveland market; a small portion is in [[Mahoning County, Ohio|Mahoning County]], home to Youngstown. However, it was later decided to reorient WNEO to serve Youngstown and sign on a satellite station to serve Akron and Cleveland. That station, WEAO, signed on the air more than two years later on September 21, 1975. Prior to WEAO's sign-on, the channel 49 allocation in the Cleveland/Akron market was occupied by Akron-based WAKR-TV from 1953 to 1967, when that station moved to UHF channel 23 (WAKR now operates as [[Ion Television]] [[owned-and-operated station]] [[WVPX-TV]]).\n\nUntil October 1, 2008, WEAO and WNEO were jointly branded as \"PBS 45 & 49\". On October 1, 2008 at 5:30&nbsp;a.m., WNEO and WEAO changed their on-air branding to \"[[Connecticut Western Reserve|Western Reserve]] PBS\", as part of the parent organization's overall branding change to Western Reserve Public Media.<ref>[http://www.westernreservepbs.org/news/newname08.htm PBS 45 & 49 to Change Name to Western Reserve Public Media]</ref> The rebranding was done to make the station's identity better reflect the viewing area, and due to the fact that the combined WNEO/WEAO operations are broadcast on different cable, satellite and [[UHF]] antenna channels in their respective service areas.<ref>[http://www.westernreservepbs.org/newname.htm PBS 45 & 49 Announces New Name and Stakes Its Claim in the Western Reserve]</ref>\n\n==Digital television==\n\n===Digital channels===\nThe stations' digital signals are [[Multiplex (TV)|multiplexed]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! [[Digital subchannel#United States|Channel]]\n! [[Display resolution|Video]]\n! [[Aspect ratio (image)|Aspect]]\n! [[Program and System Information Protocol#What PSIP does|PSIP Short Name]]\n! Programming<ref>[http://www.rabbitears.info/market.php?request=station_search&callsign=WNEO#station RabbitEars TV Query for WNEO]</ref><ref>[http://www.rabbitears.info/market.php?request=station_search&callsign=WEAO#station RabbitEars TV Query for WEAO]</ref>\n|-\n| 45.1<br>49.1 || [[720p]] || rowspan=3|[[16:9]] || WNEO-D1<br>WEAO-D1 || Main programming / [[PBS]] \n|-\n| 45.2<br>49.2 || rowspan=\"2\"|[[480i]] || WNEO-D2<br>WEAO-D2 || Fusion: [[The Ohio Channel]] 9 a.m.\u20135 p.m.<br>[[NHK Newsline]]/[[BBC World News]]/[[DW News]] 5 p.m.\u20136:30 p.m.<br>Educational [[independent station (North America)|independent]]: 7 p.m.\u201311 p.m.<br>[[Classic Arts Showcase]] 11 p.m\u20139 a.m.; \nSaturday and Sunday 11 p.m.\u2013noon\n|-\n| 45.3<br>49.3 || WNEO-D3<br>WEAO-D3 || [[First Nations Experience|FNX]]\n|}\n\nWNEO and WEAO carried [[Create (TV channel)|Create]] on digital channels 45.3 and 49.3 and the [[Ohio Channel]] on digital channels 45.4 and 49.4 until August 2007, when the two subchannels were removed to make room for their high definition feeds. The analog simulcast of WNEO/WEAO remained on digital channels 45.2 and 49.2 until the June 12, 2009 digital transition, when they were replaced with Western Reserve PBS Fusion, a local service which aired concerts and music-related programs until August 1, 2009, at which point it switched to a mix of local programming; WNEO/WEAO then added [[MHz Worldview]] to digital channels 45.3 and 49.3 on June 13.<ref>http://westernreservepublicmedia.org/digital.htm</ref> WNEO and WEAO carried [[V-Me]] on digital channels 45.4 and 49.4 on September 19, 2009. The channel was discontinued in April 2017.\n\n===Analog-to-digital conversion===\nWNEO discontinued regular programming on its analog signal, over [[Ultra high frequency|UHF]] channel 45, on November 19, 2008. Two days later on November 21, the station's digital signal relocated from its pre-transition UHF channel 46 to channel 45 for post-transition operations.<ref name=\"DTV Designations\">{{cite web |url=http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |title=DTV Tentative Channel Designations for the First and Second Rounds |format=PDF |accessdate=2012-03-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130829004251/http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |archivedate=2013-08-29 }}</ref>\n\nWEAO discontinued regular programming on its analog signal, over [[Ultra high frequency|UHF]] channel 49, on June 12, 2009, the official date in which full-power television stations in the United States [[Digital television transition in the United States|transitioned from analog to digital broadcasts]] under federal mandate. The station's digital signal remained on its pre-transition UHF channel 50,<ref name=\"DTV Designations\"/> using [[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]] to display the station's [[virtual channel]] as its former UHF analog channel 49.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://westernreservepublicmedia.org/ WNEO/WEAO official website]\n*[https://westernreservepublicmedia.org/facts.htm Station history]\n*{{TVQ|WNEO}}\n**{{TVQ|W44CR-D}}\n*{{TVQ|WEAO}}\n*{{BIA|WNEO|TV|TV}}\n*{{BIA|WEAO|TV|TV}}\n\n{{Youngstown, Ohio TV}}\n{{Cleveland TV}}\n{{PBS Ohio}}\n\n[[Category:Alliance, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Kent, Ohio]]\n[[Category:PBS member stations]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1973]]\n[[Category:1973 establishments in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Youngstown, Ohio|NEO]]\n[[Category:Kent State University]]\n[[Category:University of Akron]]\n[[Category:Youngstown State University]]\n[[Category:First Nations Experience affiliates]]\n[[Category:Classic Arts Showcase affiliates]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|PBS member station in Alliance, Ohio}}\n{{for|the WEAO radio station in Columbus, Ohio|WOSU (AM)}}\n{{Infobox broadcast\n| call_letters             = WNEO\n| city                     = Alliance, Ohio\n| station_logo             = Western Reserve PBS logo (2019).png\n| station_branding         = PBS Western Reserve\n| station_slogan           = \n| digital                  = 45 ([[ultra high frequency|UHF]])<br>''(to move to 29 (UHF))''\n| virtual                  = 45 ([[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]])\n| subchannels              = \n| other_chs                = \n| affiliations             = '''45.1:''' [[PBS]]<br>'''45.2:''' Fusion<br>'''45.3:''' [[First Nations Experience|FNX]] \n| owner                    = Western Reserve Public Media\n| licensee                 = Northeastern Educational Television of Ohio, Inc.\n| location                 = [[Alliance, Ohio|Alliance]]/[[Youngstown, Ohio]]\n| country                  = United States\n| airdate                  = {{start date and age|1973|05|30|p=y}}\n| enddate                  = \n| callsign_meaning         = '''N'''orth '''E'''astern '''O'''hio\n| sister_stations          = \n| former_callsigns         = \n| former_channel_numbers   = '''Analog:'''<br>45 (UHF, 1973\u20132008)<br>'''Digital:'''<br>46 (UHF, 2003\u20132008)\n| former_affiliations      = \n| effective_radiated_power = 500 [[kilowatt|kW]]<br>365 kW ([[construction permit|CP]])\n| HAAT                     = {{convert|253|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}<br>{{convert|251.1|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} (CP)\n| facility_id              = 49439\n| coordinates              = {{coord|40|54|23.2|N|80|54|39.3|W|type:landmark_scale:2000}}\n| licensing_authority      = [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]]\n| homepage                 = {{URL|https://westernreservepublicmedia.org/}}\n}}\n{{Infobox broadcast\n| call_letters             = WEAO<br>''([[Broadcast relay station#Satellite stations|satellite]] of WNEO)''\n| city                     = Akron, Ohio\n| station_logo             = \n| station_branding         = see WNEO infobox\n| station_slogan           = \n| digital                  = 24 (UHF)<br>''(shared with [[WRLM (TV)|WRLM]])''\n| virtual                  = 49 (PSIP)\n| subchannels              = \n| other_chs                = \n| affiliations             = '''49.1:''' PBS<br>'''49.2:''' Fusion<br>'''49.3:''' FNX \n| owner                    = Western Reserve Public Media\n| licensee                 = Northeastern Educational Television of Ohio, Inc.\n| location                 = [[Akron, Ohio|Akron]]/[[Canton, Ohio]]\n| country                  = United States\n| airdate                  = {{start date and age|1975|09|21|p=y}}\n| enddate                  = \n| callsign_meaning         = '''EA'''stern '''O'''hio\n| sister_stations          = \n| former_callsigns         = \n| former_channel_numbers   = '''Analog:'''<br>49 (UHF, 1975\u20132009)<br>'''Digital:'''<br>50 (UHF, 2004\u20132019)\n| former_affiliations      = \n| effective_radiated_power = 550 kW ([[special temporary authority|STA]])<br>191 kW ([[construction permit|CP]])\n| HAAT                     = {{convert|215.5|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} (STA)<br>{{convert|293.6|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} (CP)\n| facility_id              = 49421\n| coordinates              = {{coord|41|4|58|N|81|38|1|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|name=WEAO}}\n| licensing_authority      = FCC\n| homepage                 = \n}}\n'''WNEO''', [[virtual channel|virtual]] and [[ultra high frequency|UHF]] [[digital terrestrial television|digital]] channel 45, is a Public Broadcasting Service ([[PBS]]) [[Network affiliate#Member stations|member]] [[television station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Alliance, Ohio]], United States. The station's programming is [[simulcast]] on full-time [[Broadcast relay station#Satellite stations|satellite]] '''WEAO''' (virtual channel 49, UHF digital channel 24) in [[Akron, Ohio|Akron]]. The two stations utilize the unified brand '''PBS Western Reserve'''. WNEO is the PBS member station of record for the [[Youngstown, Ohio|Youngstown]] [[media market|market]], while WEAO provides the [[Cleveland]] market with a second choice for PBS programming alongside the market's primary PBS station, [[WVIZ]] (channel 25).\n\nWNEO and WEAO are owned by Northeastern Educational Television of Ohio, which is a consortium of the [[University of Akron]], [[Kent State University]] and [[Youngstown State University]]. The two stations operate from studios on Kent State's campus in [[Kent, Ohio|Kent]],<ref>{{cite web | title= Organization Profile| url= http://westernreservepublicmedia.org/FACTS.HTM?b1b7cb08| work= WesternReservePublicMedia.org| publisher= Western Reserve Public Media| year= 2009|quote= ''The operations center, administrative offices, main studio and location of public files are housed at 1750 Campus Center Drive, Kent, Ohio, 44240. The organization\u2019s Western Reserve Production Hub is located on the first floor of the United Building in downtown Akron.''| accessdate=21 May 2009}}</ref> northeast of Akron and roughly west of Youngstown. WNEO's transmitter is located in [[Salem, Ohio|Salem]], while WEAO's transmitter is based in [[Copley Township, Summit County, Ohio|Copley Township]].\n\nWNEO also operates '''W44CR-D''', a [[low-power broadcasting#Television|low-power]] digital [[Broadcast relay station#Broadcast translators|translator]] in Youngstown, which serves low-lying areas in the [[Mahoning Valley]] that are not covered from the main WNEO signal. The digital translator, which signed on the air in 2009, is a conversion of a former [[analog television|analog]] translator, W58AM, which broadcast at the same location.<ref>[http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/tvq?call=W44CR-D FCC TV query for W44CR-D]</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Wneo Weao.PNG|115px|thumb|left|WNEO/WEAO's former logo as \"PBS 45 & 49\".]]\n[[File:Wneo weao wr.png|115px|thumb|left|First WNEO/WEAO logo as \"Western Reserve PBS\"; used until November 4, 2019.]]\nWNEO first signed on the air on May 30, 1973. It was originally intended to serve all of northeast Ohio from Youngstown to Cleveland. Its city of license, Alliance, is split between both major markets in the region. Most of the city is in [[Stark County, Ohio|Stark County]], which is in the Cleveland market; a small portion is in [[Mahoning County, Ohio|Mahoning County]], home to Youngstown. However, it was later decided to reorient WNEO to serve Youngstown and sign on a satellite station to serve Akron and Cleveland. That station, WEAO, signed on the air more than two years later on September 21, 1975. Prior to WEAO's sign-on, the channel 49 allocation in the Cleveland/Akron market was occupied by Akron-based WAKR-TV from 1953 to 1967, when that station moved to UHF channel 23 (WAKR now operates as [[Ion Television]] [[owned-and-operated station]] [[WVPX-TV]]).\n\nUntil October 1, 2008, WEAO and WNEO were jointly branded as \"PBS 45 & 49\". On October 1, 2008 at 5:30&nbsp;a.m., WNEO and WEAO changed their on-air branding to \"[[Connecticut Western Reserve|Western Reserve]] PBS\", as part of the parent organization's overall branding change to Western Reserve Public Media.<ref>[http://www.westernreservepbs.org/news/newname08.htm PBS 45 & 49 to Change Name to Western Reserve Public Media]</ref> The rebranding was done to make the station's identity better reflect the viewing area, and due to the fact that the combined WNEO/WEAO operations are broadcast on different cable, satellite and [[UHF]] antenna channels in their respective service areas.<ref>[http://www.westernreservepbs.org/newname.htm PBS 45 & 49 Announces New Name and Stakes Its Claim in the Western Reserve]</ref>\n\n==Digital television==\n\n===Digital channels===\nThe stations' digital signals are [[Multiplex (TV)|multiplexed]]:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! [[Digital subchannel#United States|Channel]]\n! [[Display resolution|Video]]\n! [[Aspect ratio (image)|Aspect]]\n! [[Program and System Information Protocol#What PSIP does|PSIP Short Name]]\n! Programming<ref>[http://www.rabbitears.info/market.php?request=station_search&callsign=WNEO#station RabbitEars TV Query for WNEO]</ref><ref>[http://www.rabbitears.info/market.php?request=station_search&callsign=WEAO#station RabbitEars TV Query for WEAO]</ref>\n|-\n| 45.1<br>49.1 || [[720p]] || rowspan=3|[[16:9]] || WNEO-D1<br>WEAO-D1 || Main programming / [[PBS]] \n|-\n| 45.2<br>49.2 || rowspan=\"2\"|[[480i]] || WNEO-D2<br>WEAO-D2 || Fusion: [[The Ohio Channel]] 9 a.m.\u20135 p.m.<br>[[NHK Newsline]]/[[BBC World News]]/[[DW News]] 5 p.m.\u20136:30 p.m.<br>Educational [[independent station (North America)|independent]]: 7 p.m.\u201311 p.m.<br>[[Classic Arts Showcase]] 11 p.m\u20139 a.m.; \nSaturday and Sunday 11 p.m.\u2013noon\n|-\n| 45.3<br>49.3 || WNEO-D3<br>WEAO-D3 || [[First Nations Experience|FNX]]\n|}\n\nWNEO and WEAO carried [[Create (TV channel)|Create]] on digital channels 45.3 and 49.3 and the [[Ohio Channel]] on digital channels 45.4 and 49.4 until August 2007, when the two subchannels were removed to make room for their high definition feeds. The analog simulcast of WNEO/WEAO remained on digital channels 45.2 and 49.2 until the June 12, 2009 digital transition, when they were replaced with Western Reserve PBS Fusion, a local service which aired concerts and music-related programs until August 1, 2009, at which point it switched to a mix of local programming; WNEO/WEAO then added [[MHz Worldview]] to digital channels 45.3 and 49.3 on June 13.<ref>http://westernreservepublicmedia.org/digital.htm</ref> WNEO and WEAO carried [[V-Me]] on digital channels 45.4 and 49.4 on September 19, 2009. The channel was discontinued in April 2017.\n\n===Analog-to-digital conversion===\nWNEO discontinued regular programming on its analog signal, over [[Ultra high frequency|UHF]] channel 45, on November 19, 2008. Two days later on November 21, the station's digital signal relocated from its pre-transition UHF channel 46 to channel 45 for post-transition operations.<ref name=\"DTV Designations\">{{cite web |url=http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |title=DTV Tentative Channel Designations for the First and Second Rounds |format=PDF |accessdate=2012-03-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130829004251/http://hraunfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DA-06-1082A2.pdf |archivedate=2013-08-29 }}</ref>\n\nWEAO discontinued regular programming on its analog signal, over [[Ultra high frequency|UHF]] channel 49, on June 12, 2009, the official date in which full-power television stations in the United States [[Digital television transition in the United States|transitioned from analog to digital broadcasts]] under federal mandate. The station's digital signal remained on its pre-transition UHF channel 50,<ref name=\"DTV Designations\"/> using [[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]] to display the station's [[virtual channel]] as its former UHF analog channel 49.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://westernreservepublicmedia.org/ WNEO/WEAO official website]\n*[https://westernreservepublicmedia.org/facts.htm Station history]\n*{{TVQ|WNEO}}\n**{{TVQ|W44CR-D}}\n*{{TVQ|WEAO}}\n*{{BIA|WNEO|TV|TV}}\n*{{BIA|WEAO|TV|TV}}\n\n{{Youngstown, Ohio TV}}\n{{Cleveland TV}}\n{{PBS Ohio}}\n\n[[Category:Alliance, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Kent, Ohio]]\n[[Category:PBS member stations]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1973]]\n[[Category:1973 establishments in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Television stations in Youngstown, Ohio|NEO]]\n[[Category:Kent State University]]\n[[Category:University of Akron]]\n[[Category:Youngstown State University]]\n[[Category:First Nations Experience affiliates]]\n[[Category:Classic Arts Showcase affiliates]]\n", "name_user": "Armando619", "label": "safe", "comment": "update page and information", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WNEO"}
{"title_page": "Hidden Valley Road", "text_new": "{{Infobox book\n| name = Hidden Valley Road: Inside the Mind of an American Family\n| image = Hidden Valley Road (Robert Kolker).png\n| alt = \n| caption = Cover of first edition\n| author = [[Robert Kolker]]\n| audio_read_by = Sean Pratt<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.penguinrandomhouseaudio.com/book/566406/hidden-valley-road/ |title=Hidden Valley Road by Robert Kolker |website=[[Penguin Random House Audio]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n| cover_artist = \n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| subject = {{flatlist|\n* Galvin family\n* [[schizophrenia]]\n}}\n| set_in = \n| publisher = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]\n| pub_date = April 7, 2020\n| media_type = Print (hardcover and paperback), e-book, audiobook\n| pages = \n| awards = \n| isbn = 978-0-385-54376-7\n| isbn_note = (hardcover)\n| oclc = 1148170726\n| dewey = 616.89/80092\n| congress = RC514 .K648 2020\n| website = {{URL|hidden-valley-road.com}}\n}}\n'''''Hidden Valley Road: Inside the Mind of an American Family''''' is a 2020 non-fiction book by [[Robert Kolker]]. It is an account of the Galvin family, a midcentury American family with twelve children, six of them diagnosed with schizophrenia, that became science\u2019s great hope in the quest to understand the disease.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/566406/hidden-valley-road-by-robert-kolker/ |title=Hidden Valley Road by Robert Kolker |website=[[Penguin Random House]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://slate.com/culture/2020/04/hidden-valley-road-robert-kolker-interview-schizophrenia.html |title=Six Brothers With Schizophrenia Fascinated Researchers. A New Book Explores the Family's Trauma. |last=Miller |first=Laura |authorlink=Laura Miller (writer) |date=April 8, 2020 |website=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/04/05/826695581/in-hidden-valley-road-a-familys-journey-helps-shift-the-science-of-mental-illnes |title=In 'Hidden Valley Road,' A Family's Journey Helps Shift The Science Of Mental Illness |last=Garcia-Navarro |first=Lulu |authorlink=Lulu Garcia-Navarro |date=April 5, 2020 |website=[[Weekend Edition Sunday]] |publisher=[[NPR]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe book was selected for the revival of [[Oprah's Book Club]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://apnews.com/729a8af97adb8f7e6fd31c5fe56d09b0 |title=Winfrey chooses \"Hidden Valley Road\" for book club |last=Italie |first=Hillel |date=April 7, 2020 |website=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/books/author-interviews/hidden-valley-road-robert-kolker-oprah-book-club/ |title=Author Robert Kolker takes us inside ''Hidden Valley Road'', Oprah's latest book club pick |last=Rankin |first=Seija |date=April 7, 2020 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/books/story/2020-04-07/hidden-valley-road-traces-schizophrenias-devastation-of-a-boomer-family |title=Schizophrenia devastated a family: Robert Kolker did their story justice |last=Tuttle |first=Kate |date=April 7, 2020 |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/oprah-winfrey-book-club-robert-kolker-1496642 |title=Oprah's Book Club Names Robert Kolker's 'Hidden Valley Road' the New Pick For April |last=Williams |first=Janice |date=April 7, 2020 |website=[[Newsweek]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' praised the book's \"astounding depth and empathy\" and Kolker's account of schizophrenia's history and the complicated atmosphere and relationships between members of the Galvin family.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/robert-kolker/hidden-valley-road/ |title=Hidden Valley Road: Inside the Mind of an American Family by Robert Kolker |date=December 15, 2019 |website=[[Kirkus Reviews]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' called the book a \"haunting and memorable\" account of multi-generational mental illness and praised Kolker's \"taut and often heartbreaking narrative.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-385-54376-7 |title=Nonfiction Book Review: Hidden Valley Road: Inside the Mind of an American Family by Robert Kolker |date=February 4, 2020 |website=[[Publishers Weekly]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:American biographies]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Books about mental health]]\n[[Category:Doubleday (publisher) books]]\n[[Category:Schizophrenia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book\n| name = Hidden Valley Road: Inside the Mind of an American Family\n| image = Hidden Valley Road (Robert Kolker).png\n| alt = \n| caption = Cover of first edition\n| author = [[Robert Kolker]]\n| audio_read_by = Sean Pratt<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.penguinrandomhouseaudio.com/book/566406/hidden-valley-road/ |title=Hidden Valley Road by Robert Kolker |website=[[Penguin Random House Audio]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n| cover_artist = \n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| subject = {{flatlist|\n* Galvin family\n* [[schizophrenia]]\n}}\n| set_in = \n| publisher = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]\n| pub_date = April 7, 2020\n| media_type = Print (hardcover and paperback), e-book, audiobook\n| pages = \n| awards = \n| isbn = 978-0-385-54376-7\n| isbn_note = (hardcover)\n| oclc = 1148170726\n| dewey = 616.89/80092\n| congress = RC514 .K648 2020\n| website = {{URL|hidden-valley-road.com}}\n}}\n'''''Hidden Valley Road: Inside the Mind of an American Family''''' is a 2020 non-fiction book by [[Robert Kolker]]. It is an account of the Galvin family, a midcentury American family with twelve children, six of them diagnosed with schizophrenia, that became science\u2019s great hope in the quest to understand the disease.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/566406/hidden-valley-road-by-robert-kolker/ |title=Hidden Valley Road by Robert Kolker |website=[[Penguin Random House]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://slate.com/culture/2020/04/hidden-valley-road-robert-kolker-interview-schizophrenia.html |title=Six Brothers With Schizophrenia Fascinated Researchers. A New Book Explores the Family's Trauma. |last=Miller |first=Laura |authorlink=Laura Miller (writer) |date=April 8, 2020 |website=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/04/05/826695581/in-hidden-valley-road-a-familys-journey-helps-shift-the-science-of-mental-illnes |title=In 'Hidden Valley Road,' A Family's Journey Helps Shift The Science Of Mental Illness |last=Garcia-Navarro |first=Lulu |authorlink=Lulu Garcia-Navarro |date=April 5, 2020 |website=[[Weekend Edition Sunday]] |publisher=[[NPR]] |accessdate=Aprill 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe book was selected for the revival of [[Oprah's Book Club]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://apnews.com/729a8af97adb8f7e6fd31c5fe56d09b0 |title=Winfrey chooses \"Hidden Valley Road\" for book club |last=Italie |first=Hillel |date=April 7, 2020 |website=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/books/author-interviews/hidden-valley-road-robert-kolker-oprah-book-club/ |title=Author Robert Kolker takes us inside ''Hidden Valley Road'', Oprah's latest book club pick |last=Rankin |first=Seija |date=April 7, 2020 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/books/story/2020-04-07/hidden-valley-road-traces-schizophrenias-devastation-of-a-boomer-family |title=Schizophrenia devastated a family: Robert Kolker did their story justice |last=Tuttle |first=Kate |date=April 7, 2020 |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/oprah-winfrey-book-club-robert-kolker-1496642 |title=Oprah's Book Club Names Robert Kolker's 'Hidden Valley Road' the New Pick For April |last=Williams |first=Janice |date=April 7, 2020 |website=[[Newsweek]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' praised the book's \"astounding depth and empathy\" and Kolker's account of schizophrenia's history and the complicated atmosphere and relationships between members of the Galvin family.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/robert-kolker/hidden-valley-road/ |title=Hidden Valley Road: Inside the Mind of an American Family by Robert Kolker |date=December 15, 2019 |website=[[Kirkus Reviews]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' called the book a \"haunting and memorable\" account of multi-generational mental illness and praised Kolker's \"taut and often heartbreaking narrative.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-385-54376-7 |title=Nonfiction Book Review: Hidden Valley Road: Inside the Mind of an American Family by Robert Kolker |date=February 4, 2020 |website=[[Publishers Weekly]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:American biographies]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Books about mental health]]\n[[Category:Doubleday (publisher) books]]\n[[Category:Schizophrenia]]\n", "name_user": "I grieve in stereo", "label": "safe", "comment": "c/e", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hidden_Valley_Road"}
{"title_page": "Alphonso Davies", "text_new": "{{Use Canadian English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name                = Alphonso Davies\n|image               = 20190428 DFL 1. Bundesliga FCN - FCB DSC 7707.jpg\n|image_size          =\n|caption             = Davies playing for [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] in 2019\n|fullname            = Alphonso Boyle Davies\n|birth_date          = {{birth date and age|2000|11|2}}\n|birth_place         = [[Buduburam]], Ghana\n|height              = 1.81 m<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/teams/professionals/alphonso-davies |title=Alphonso Davies Bayern Munich Profile |access-date=October 19, 2019}}</ref>\n|position            = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]], [[Defender (association football)#Wing-back|wing-back]]\n|currentclub         = [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]\n|clubnumber          = 19\n|youthyears1         = {{0|0000}}\u20132005\n|youthclubs1         = Edmonton Internationals\n|youthyears2         = 2006\u20132014\n|youthclubs2         = Edmonton Strikers\n|youthyears3         = 2015\u20132016\n|youthclubs3         = [[Vancouver Whitecaps FC Academy|Whitecaps FC Residency]]\n|years1              = 2016\n|clubs1              = [[Whitecaps FC 2]]\n|caps1               = 11\n|goals1              = 2\n|years2              = 2016\u20132018\n|clubs2              = [[Vancouver Whitecaps FC]]\n|caps2               = 65\n|goals2              = 8\n|years3              = 2019\n|clubs3              = [[FC Bayern Munich II|Bayern Munich II]]\n|caps3               = 6\n|goals3              = 0\n|years4              = 2019\u2013\n|clubs4              = [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]\n|caps4               = 27\n|goals4              = 2\n|nationalyears1      = 2016\n|nationalteam1       = [[Canada men's national under-17 soccer team|Canada U17]]\n|nationalcaps1       = 2\n|nationalgoals1      = 1\n|nationalyears2      = 2016\n|nationalteam2       = [[Canada men's national under-20 soccer team|Canada U20]]\n|nationalcaps2       = 1\n|nationalgoals2      = 0\n|nationalyears3      = 2017\u2013\n|nationalteam3       = [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]]\n|nationalcaps3       = 17\n|nationalgoals3      = 5\n|club-update         = 16:24, March 8, 2020 (UTC)\n|nationalteam-update = November 15, 2019\n}}\n\n'''Alphonso Boyle Davies''' (born November 2, 2000)<ref name=\"Canada Soccer profile\">{{Cite web |url=https://canadasoccer.com/index.php?pid=5810&t=profile |title=Alphonso Davies |publisher=Canada Soccer |access-date=March 11, 2018}}</ref> is a Canadian professional [[association football|football]]<!--Davies is a Canadian and the name of the sport in Canada is \"soccer\". MOS:TIES applies to the WP:LANGVAG used.--> player who plays as a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] and [[Left-Back|left back]] for [[Bundesliga]] club [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] and the [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada national team]]. He was the first player born in the 2000s to play in a [[Major League Soccer]] match. Davies joined Bayern in January 2019 from MLS side [[Vancouver Whitecaps FC]] on a contract lasting until 2023 for a then-MLS record transfer fee.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://fcbayern.com/de/news/2018/07/fc-bayern-verpflichtet-alphonso-davies-bis-2023 |title=FC Bayern verpflichtet Alphonso Davies bis 2023 |date=July 25, 2018 |access-date=July 25, 2018 |language=German |trans-title=Bayern commits Alphonso Davies until 2023 |website=FC Bayern Munich}}</ref><ref name=\"MLS record\" />\n\nIn June 2017, he became the youngest player to appear for the Canadian men's national team.<ref name=\"talent belies his youth\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/soccer/2017/07/05/canadian-soccer-phenom-alphonso-davies-talent-belies-his-youth.html |title=Canadian soccer phenom Alphonso Davies' talent belies his youth |last=Buhler |first=Andy |website=The Star |access-date=July 8, 2017}}</ref> By scoring two goals in a [[2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup]] match against [[French Guiana national football team|French Guiana]], he became the youngest player to score for the Canadian men's national team, the youngest to score at the [[CONCACAF Gold Cup]], and first player born in the 2000s to score at a top level international tournament.<ref name=\"becomes first\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/588/gold-cup/2017/07/07/36915632/davies-becomes-first-2000s-born-player-to-score-at-a-top |title=Davies becomes first 2000s-born player to score at a top level international tournament |last=Schuller |first=Rudi |publisher=Goal.com |access-date=July 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nDavies was born in [[Buduburam]], a refugee camp in the [[Gomoa East District]] of Ghana, to Liberian parents.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49841881 |title=Alphonso Davies: The Bayern Munich winger born in a refugee camp |date=September 26, 2019 |publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/alphonso-davies-canada-national-team-vancouver-whitecaps-mls-major-league-soccer/ |title=Whitecaps phenom Davies receives Canadian citizenship, 1st senior call-up |last=Asano |first=Naoko |website=Sportsnet |access-date=June 7, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Bayern Munich: Who is new signing Alphonso Davies?\">{{Cite news |last=Penfold |first=Chuck |url=https://www.dw.com/en/bayern-munich-who-is-new-signing-alphonso-davies/a-44824675 |title=Bayern Munich: Who is new signing Alphonso Davies? |date=July 26, 2018 |access-date=July 27, 2018 |publisher=Deutsche Welle}}</ref> His parents lived there after fleeing their homeland during the [[Second Liberian Civil War]], which displaced more than 450,000 people in [[Liberia]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://journals.lib.unb.ca/index.php/jcs/article/view/11734/12489 |title=The Civil War and the Refugee Crisis in Liberia |access-date=July 24, 2018}}</ref> When Davies was five, his family came to Canada as refugees, and moved to [[Windsor, Ontario]],<ref name=\"auto\" /><ref name=\"talent belies his youth\" /> before relocating a year later to [[Edmonton]].<ref name=\"talent belies his youth\" /><ref name=\"Bayern Munich: Who is new signing Alphonso Davies?\" /> On June 6, 2017, he officially received Canadian citizenship.<ref name=\"citizenship\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.whitecapsfc.com/post/2017/06/06/alphonso-davies-receives-canadian-citizenship-and-first-senior-call-canada |title=Alphonso Davies receives Canadian citizenship and first senior call-up to Canada |access-date=June 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Youth career===\nAfter playing for Edmonton Internationals, and Edmonton Strikers, Davies joined the [[Vancouver Whitecaps FC Residency|Whitecaps FC Residency]] in 2015 at the age of 14.<ref name=\"kicker profile\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/1-bundesliga/2018/bayern-muenchen-14/99583/spieler_alphonso-davies.html |title=Alphonso Davies |website=kicker.de |language=de |access-date=February 2, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.whitecapsfc.com/players/alphonso-davies |title=Whitecaps FC Profile: Alphonso Davies |access-date=February 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Whitecaps FC 2===\nAfter joining [[Vancouver Whitecaps FC]] during their 2016 MLS preseason tour,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theprovince.com/sports/Weber+Caps+give+youth+chance+year+Alphonso+Davies/11708472/story.html |title=Caps give youth a chance in 15-year-old Alphonso Davies |last=Weber |first=Marc |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531023646/http://www.theprovince.com/sports/weber+caps+give+youth+chance+year+alphonso+davies/11708472/story.html |archive-date=May 31, 2016 |access-date=February 24, 2016}}</ref> Davies signed with [[Whitecaps FC 2]] in the [[United Soccer League|USL]] on February 23, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.whitecapsfc.com/wfc2/post/2016/02/22/whitecaps-fc-sign-teenagers-matthew-baldisimo-and-alphonso-davies-wfc2 |title=Whitecaps FC sign teenagers Matthew Baldisimo and Alphonso Davies to WFC2 |access-date=February 24, 2016}}</ref> At the time of his signing, he became the youngest player signed to a USL contract at 15 years, 3 months. Davies made his professional debut for Whitecaps FC 2 at the age of 15 years, 5 months in April 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/wfc2/status/716433490217148416 |title=Whitecaps FC 2 on Twitter |access-date=July 17, 2016}}</ref> On May 15, 2016, he scored his first professional goal, making him the youngest goal scorer in USL history at 15 years, 6 months.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/USL/status/731961905821057024 |title=USL on Twitter |access-date=July 17, 2016}}</ref> He scored two goals in 11 games played during the [[2016 USL season|2016 season]].<ref name=\"Soccerway\">{{Cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/alphonso-davies/441396/ |title=Alphonso Davies profile |website=Soccerway}}</ref>\n\n===Vancouver Whitecaps FC===\nDavies was named to the Whitecaps roster for the [[2016 Canadian Championship]] on a short term contract.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.whitecapsfc.com/post/2016/05/31/whitecaps-fc-submit-20-man-roster-acc |title=Whitecaps FC submit 20-man roster in advance of Wednesday's Amway Canadian Championship semifinal &#124; Vancouver Whitecaps FC}}</ref> On June 1, 2016, he made his first team debut in the first leg of the Canadian Championship against the [[Ottawa Fury]] and started the second leg in Vancouver.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/WhitecapsFC/status/738176377921249281 |title=Vancouver Whitecaps on Twitter |access-date=July 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn July 15, 2016, Davies signed a first team contract with the Whitecaps through 2018, with options for the 2019 and 2020 seasons. At the time of his signing, he was the youngest active player in [[Major League Soccer]], and the third youngest player to have signed an MLS contract.<ref name=\"fifteen\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.whitecapsfc.com/post/2016/07/15/whitecaps-fc-add-15-year-old-residency-product-alphonso-davies |title=Whitecaps FC add 15-year-old Residency product Alphonso Davies to MLS roster |date=July 15, 2016 |publisher=Vancouver Whitecaps FC}}</ref> Davies made his MLS debut on July 16, 2016, becoming the second youngest player to play in MLS, behind [[Freddy Adu]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/youngster-alphonso-davies-impresses-mls-debut-whitecaps/ |title=Youngster Alphonso Davies impresses in MLS debut for Whitecaps |date=July 16, 2016 |publisher=Sportsnet}}</ref> In September 2016, he scored his first goal for the first team in the [[2016\u201317 CONCACAF Champions League]] against [[Sporting Kansas City]] in injury time to send the club through to the knockout round.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/WhitecapsFC/status/775908017636253696 |title=SCCL quarterfinal berth: CLINCHED!!! |date=September 13, 2016 |publisher=Vancouver Whitecaps FC Official Twitter}}</ref> In September 2016, Davies became the second youngest starter in MLS history when he started a game against the [[Colorado Rapids]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2016/09/24/whitecaps-alphonso-davies-15-second-youngest-starter-mls-history |title=Whitecaps' Alphonso Davies, 15, is second-youngest starter in MLS history |last=Stephen |first=Colin |date=September 24, 2016 |publisher=MLS Official Website}}</ref> On October, 2, 2016 he started against rival club [[Seattle Sounders FC]] earning a penalty kick.<ref name=\"Vancouver Whitecaps 1, Seattle Sounders 2\">{{Cite web |url=https://matchcenter.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter/2016-10-02-vancouver-whitecaps-fc-vs-seattle-sounders-fc/recap |title=Vancouver Whitecaps 1, Seattle Sounders 2 |last=Boehm |first=Charles |publisher=Major League Soccer |access-date=July 8, 2017}}</ref> During the [[2016 Vancouver Whitecaps FC season|2016 season]], Davies played in eight MLS games,<ref name=\"WorldFootball\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/alphonso-davies/2/ |title=Alphonso Davies \u00bb Club matches |publisher=World Football |access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref> four Canadian Championship games,<ref name=\"WorldFootball\" /> and three games in the CONCACAF Champions League.<ref name=\"Alphonso Davies \u00bb CONCACAF Champions League 2016/2017\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/alphonso-davies/concacaf-champions-league-2016-2017/vancouver-whitecaps/3/ |title=Alphonso Davies \u00bb CONCACAF Champions League 2016/2017 |publisher=World Football |access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his impressive early MLS appearances, Davies attracted interest and was scouted by European clubs including [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], and [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]],<ref name=\"Giants\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.metro.us/sports/source-alphonso-davies-being-trailed-by-three-english-premier-league-giants/zsJqci---b4pyPX6iT1FuM |title=Source: Alphonso Davies being trailed by three English Premier League giants |last=Dyer |first=Kristian |publisher=Metro.us |access-date=July 9, 2017}}</ref> and was also named one of the 60 best young soccer talents in the world in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/ng-interactive/2017/oct/04/next-generation-2017-60-of-the-best-young-talents-in-world-football |title=Next Generation 2017: 60 of the best young talents in world football |website=The Guardian |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2018 Vancouver Whitecaps FC season|2018 season]] opener against the [[Montreal Impact]], Davies scored his first goal in MLS action, and assisted on a [[Kei Kamara]] goal.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://matchcenter.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter/2018-03-04-vancouver-whitecaps-fc-vs-montreal-impact/recap |title=Recap: Vancouver Whitecaps FC vs. Montreal Impact |last=Boehm |first=Charles |date=March 4, 2018 |website=MLS}}</ref> On June 10, 2018, he scored a goal and got three assists in a 5\u20132 win over [[Orlando City SC|Orlando City]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/soccer/article-alphonso-davies-has-goal-three-assists-to-lead-whitecaps-past-orlando/ |title=Alphonso Davies has goal, three assists to lead Whitecaps past Orlando City |last=Dyck |first=Darryl |date=June 10, 2018 |website=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> Davies scored two goals and provided two assists to help his side defeat [[Minnesota United FC (2010\u201316)|Minnesota United]] with a 4\u20132 victory on July 29.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2018/07/29/bayern-munich-bound-alphonso-davies-destroys-loons-whitecaps-win |title=Bayern Munich-bound Alphonso Davies destroys Loons as Whitecaps win |publisher=Major League Soccer |access-date=July 29, 2018}}</ref> On June 29, 2018, Davies was included in the MLS All-Star roster for the [[2018 MLS All-Star Game]] on August 1 against [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]].<ref name=\"All-Star\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/all-star/2018/rosters/mls-all-star-team |title=2018 MLS All-Star Roster |date=June 29, 2018 |website=MLSsoccer.com |publisher=[[Major League Soccer]] |access-date=June 16, 2018}}</ref> Davies made an appearance during the match, which finished as a 3\u20135 penalty shoot-out loss following a 1\u20131 draw.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Roberson |first=Doug |url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/martinez-mls-all-stars-tie-juventus-front-record-crowd/7xztCXmW1mO712v99nD8NL/ |title=Martinez scores but MLS All-Stars fall to Juventus in front of record crowd |date=August 1, 2018 |access-date=August 1, 2018 |publisher=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] |website=AJC.com}}</ref> Davies was named the Vancouver Whitecaps FC Player of the Year on October 24,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Adams |first=J.J. |url=https://theprovince.com/sports/soccer/mls/vancouver-whitecaps/alphonso-davies-named-whitecaps-player-of-the-year |title=Alphonso Davies named Caps' player of the year |date=October 24, 2018 |work=[[The Province]] |access-date=October 30, 2018}}</ref> and also received the Whitecaps' Goal of the Year award.<ref name=\"POTY\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.whitecapsfc.com/post/2018/10/24/winners-announced-2018-whitecaps-fc-player-awards-presented-bmo |title=Winners announced for 2018 Whitecaps FC Player Awards, presented by BMO |date=October 24, 2018 |access-date=October 30, 2018 |publisher=[[Vancouver Whitecaps FC]] |website=whitecapsfc.com}}</ref> In Davies' final game for Vancouver on October 28, he scored both goals in a 2\u20131 victory over the Portland Timbers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4605129/alphonso-davies-final-vancouver-game/ |title=Emotional sendoff as Alphonso Davies plays final game as Vancouver Whitecap |last=Little |first=Simon |date=October 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Bayern Munich===\n\nOn July 25, 2018, Vancouver announced that it had agreed to a multi-million-dollar transfer of Davies to [[Bundesliga]] club [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]], with Davies seeing out the 2018 MLS season with Vancouver, before joining Bayern in January 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44964070 |title=Alphonso Davies: Bayern Munich sign 17-year-old for MLS record fee |date=July 26, 2018 |publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.whitecapsfc.com/post/2018/07/25/whitecaps-fc-agree-mls-record-breaking-transfer-homegrown-midfielder-alphonso-davies |title=Whitecaps FC agree to MLS record-breaking transfer of Homegrown midfielder Alphonso Davies to Germany's most storied club FC Bayern Munich |date=July 25, 2018 |publisher=Vancouver Whitecaps FC |access-date=July 25, 2018}}</ref> The base fee for the transfer is US$13.5&nbsp;million, with performance-related bonuses that total $22&nbsp;million, a then-record for MLS,<ref name=\"MLS record\">{{Cite news |last=Lindberg |first=Austin |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/soccer-transfers/story/3573807/bayern-munich-sign-canadian-teen-alphonso-davies-in-mls-record-deal |title=Bayern Munich sign Canadian teen Alphonso Davies in MLS-record deal |date=July 25, 2018 |access-date=July 25, 2018 |publisher=ESPN}}</ref> later eclipsed by the transfer of [[Miguel Almiron]] to [[Newcastle United]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2019/01/31/miguel-almiron-completes-record-transfer-atlanta-newcastle |title=Miguel Almiron completes record transfer from Atlanta to Newcastle |date=January 31, 2019 |publisher=MLS Soccer |access-date=January 31, 2019}}</ref> Davies had his first training session with Bayern on November 21, 2018,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/bayern-munich/story/3705715/canadas-alphonso-davies-very-excited-as-bayern-munich-career-begins |title=Canada's Alphonso Davies 'very excited' as Bayern Munich career begins |last=Uersfeld |first=Stephan |date=November 22, 2018 |publisher=ESPN |access-date=November 22, 2018}}</ref> and debuted on January 12, 2019 against [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]] in the [[Telekom Cup]] championship finale, which Bayern won on penalties following a scoreless draw.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.whitecapsfc.com/post/2019/01/13/alphonso-davies-shows-attacking-flair-bayern-munich-debut |title=Alphonso Davies shows attacking flair in Bayern Munich debut |last=Devji |first=Farhan |date=January 13, 2019 |access-date=January 19, 2019}}</ref> Davies made his Bundesliga debut on January 27 against [[VfB Stuttgart]], appearing as a late substitute for [[Kingsley Coman]] in a 3\u20131 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/alphonso-davies-bundesliga-debut-bayern-1.4995003 |title=Alphonso Davies makes league debut for Bayern Munich in win |date=January 27, 2019 |access-date=February 1, 2019}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Bayern on March 17, netting the final goal in a 6\u20130 rout of [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz 05]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2019/03/17/alphonso-davies-bayern-munich-first-goal-watch-mainz |title=Alphonso Davies Scores First Ever Goal for Bayern Munich in Huge Win Over Mainz |last=Echegaray |first=Luis Miguel |date=March 17, 2019 |website=Sports Illustrated |access-date=March 17, 2019}}</ref> In doing so, and at the age of 18 years, 4 months and 15 days, he became the youngest player since [[Roque Santa Cruz]], twenty years prior, to score for the club. He is the first Canadian international to score for Bayern.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/bayern-munich-mainz-live-line-ups-stats-thomas-muller-james-rodriguez-hummels-3035 |title=James Rodriguez hat-trick and maiden Alphonso Davies goal send Bayern Munich top after crushing Mainz win |date=March 17, 2019 |access-date=March 18, 2019 |publisher=Bundesliga}}</ref> On May 18, 2019, Davies won his first Bundesliga title as Bayern finished two points above [[Borussia Dortmund|Dortmund]] with 78 points. A week later, Davies won his first [[DFB-Pokal]] as Bayern defeated [[RB Leipzig]] 3\u20130 in the [[2019 DFB-Pokal Final]]. Davies was not selected for the match day squad.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/rb-leipzig-bayern-munich-live-dfb-cup-final-james-rodriguez-lewandowski-neuer-4678 |title=Robert Lewandowski hits brace as Bayern Munich beat RB Leipzig in DFB Cup final to seal the double |publisher=bundesliga.com |access-date=May 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDavies made his first Bundesliga start with Bayern on matchday nine of the [[2019\u201320 Bundesliga]] season, going the full 90 minutes in a 2\u20131 home victory over [[1. FC Union Berlin|Union Berlin]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/alphonso-davies-inspired-by-robert-lewandowski-bayern-munich-7771 |title=Davies lauds Lewandowki |website=bundesliga.com |access-date=October 28, 2019}}</ref> He made his first [[UEFA Champions League]] start on November 6, 2019, in a 2\u20130 victory against [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/bayern-munich-olympiacos-champions-league-live-line-ups-stats-lewandowski-7935 |title=Robert Lewandowski on target again as Bayern Munich down Olympiacos to reach UEFA Champions League last 16 |date=November 6, 2019 |website=bundesliga.com |access-date=November 6, 2019}}</ref> Throughout the 2019\u201320 season, Davies would play as a left back to allow [[David Alaba]] to play at centre back. Davies would earn high praise during his time in that role, being considered one of the best left backs in the world.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/alphonso-davies-is-the-bayern-munich-teen-one-of-the-world-s-best-left-backs-9896 |title=Alphonso Davies: Is the Bayern Munich teenager one of the best left-backs in the world? |date=February 22, 2020 |website=Bundesliga}}</ref>{{better source|reason=the Bundesliga is the league Davies plays in, and therefore has a conflict of interest to make him look good|date=February 2020}} On February 25, 2020, Davies set-up [[Robert Lewandowski]]'s goal in a 3\u20130 away win over [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in the first leg of the round of 16 of the [[2019\u201320 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|UEFA Champions League]]; his performance during the match was widely praised in the media, with pundit [[Gary Lineker]] commenting that Davies played \"beautifully,\" while former U.S. international [[Stuart Holden]] described him as a \"world class left back.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6595963/alphonso-davies-bayern-munich-chelsea-champions-league/ |title=Alphonso Davies shines in Bayern Munich\u2019s 3-0 Champions League win at Chelsea |work=Global News |date=February 25, 2020 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Alphonso_Davies_2018.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Davies with Canada during a match against [[Dominica national football team|Dominica]] at [[BMO Field]] in [[Toronto]], October 16, 2018]]\n===Youth teams===\nAlthough a Liberian citizen by birth, Davies was called to numerous Canadian U-15 and U-18 camps in 2014 and 2015.<ref name=\"Canada Soccer profile\" /> On March 17, 2016, he was called up to the Canada U20 squad for a friendly against England U20.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://canadasoccer.com/canada-soccer-selects-players-for-england-youth-friendly-p159270 |title=Canada Soccer selects players for England youth friendly |publisher=Canada Soccer |access-date=July 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/alphonso-davies-soccer-1.3494605 |title=Alphonso Davies joins Canada's U-20 soccer team |access-date=March 27, 2016}}</ref> In November 2016, Davies attended a Canadian U-17 camp, where he scored against [[Jamaica national under-17 football team|Jamaica]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theprovince.com/sports/alphonso+davies+scores+canadas+under17+squad+friendly+over+jamaica/12441846/story.html |title=Alphonso Davies scores for Canada's under-17 squad in friendly win over Jamaica |date=November 26, 2016 |publisher=Vancouver Province |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129144149/http://www.theprovince.com/sports/alphonso+davies+scores+canadas+under17+squad+friendly+over+jamaica/12441846/story.html |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |access-date=November 29, 2016 |agency=The Canadian Press}}</ref> In 2016, he was named the Canada U17 Male Player of the Year for his performances with the U-17 and U-20 squads in friendlies.<ref name=\"U17 POTY 2016\">{{Cite web |url=http://canadasoccer.com/davies-and-rose-win-2016-canadian-u-17-players-of-the-year-p160230 |title=Davies and Rose win 2016 Canadian U-17 Players of the Year |date=December 13, 2016 |publisher=Canada Soccer}}</ref> In March 2017, Davies stated in an interview that, \"to be able to represent Canada, it is one of my dreams.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theprovince.com/sports/soccer/mls/vancouver-whitecaps/his-talent-was-evident-whitecaps-teenage-soccer-phenom-turning-heads |title='His talent was evident': Alphonso Davies is dropping jaws, one at a time |date=March 30, 2017 |website=Vancouver Province}}</ref> In 2017, he was named the Canada U17 Male Player of the Year for a second time due to his performances with the senior team.<ref name=\"U17 POTY 2017\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.canadasoccer.com/davies-huitema-named-canadian-u-17-players-of-the-year-for-canada-soccer-p161311-preview-1 |title=Davies & Huitema named Canadian U-17 Players of the Year for Canada Soccer |date=December 11, 2017 |website=Canada Soccer}}</ref>\n\n===Senior team===\nOn June 6, 2017, Davies passed his citizenship test and officially became a citizen of Canada, making him eligible to play for the [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada national team]].<ref name=\"citizenship\" /> On the same day, Davies was added to a senior team camp for a friendly against [[Cura\u00e7ao national football team|Cura\u00e7ao]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Clipperton |first=Joshua |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/mls/alphonso-davies-receives-canadian-citizenship-first-national-team-call-up-1.4148883 |title=Teen's soccer journey takes him from refugee camp to Canada's national team |date=June 6, 2017 |access-date=October 30, 2018 |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |agency=[[The Canadian Press]]}}</ref> as well as Canada's preliminary 40-man roster for the [[2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2017 Gold Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://canadasoccer.com/canada-soccer-releases-40-man-provisional-list-for-concacaf-gold-cup-p160880 |title=Canada Soccer releases 40-man Provisional List for CONCACAF Gold Cup |date=June 6, 2017 |website=Canada Soccer}}</ref> Davies would debut for the senior team in the friendly against Cura\u00e7ao at the age of 16, making him the youngest player to play for the national team.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Heidenreich |first=Phil |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/3526091/teen-soccer-star-from-edmonton-impresses-in-history-making-debut-for-team-canada/ |title=Teen soccer star from Edmonton impresses in history making debut for Team Canada |date=June 14, 2017 |access-date=October 30, 2018 |publisher=[[Global News]] |website=globalnews.ca}}</ref> On June 27, Davies was named to the final 23-man squad for the [[2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2017 Gold Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/06/27/canada-names-nine-mls-players-23-man-concacaf-gold-cup-roster |title=Canada names nine MLS players to 23-man CONCACAF Gold Cup roster |last=Zeitlin |first=Dave |date=June 27, 2017}}</ref> In Canada's first match of that tournament, Davies scored twice in a 4\u20132 victory over [[French Guiana national football team|French Guiana]]. The goals make him the youngest goalscorer in Gold Cup history.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/canada-french-guiana-gold-cup-recap-1.4195412 |title=Teen Alphonso Davies scores 2 in Canada's Gold Cup win |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |access-date=July 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/canada-french-guiana-concacaf-gold-cup-alphonso-davies-octavio-zambrano/ |title=Canada walks away with win and lessons learned in Gold Cup opener |website=Sportsnet.ca |access-date=July 8, 2017}}</ref> He then scored in their second match against [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]] to earn a 1\u20131 draw.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.canadasoccer.com/canada-stays-atop-group-a-with-impressive-1-1-draw-with-costa-rica-at-concacaf-gold-cup-p161011 |title=Canada stays atop Group A with impressive 1:1 draw with Costa Rica at CONCACAF Gold Cup |website=canadasoccer.com}}</ref> Davies went on to win the Golden Boot as the tournament's top scorer, the Young Player of the Tournament award, and was included in the tournament's Best XI selection.<ref name=\"trio of Gold Cup awards\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/ca/soccer/news/gold-cup-2017-canadas-davies-named-best-young-player/wqonov7ykcdy1aa7d63qc2xn0 |title=Canada's Alphonso Davies wins trio of Gold Cup awards |last=Schuller |first=Rudi |publisher=Sporting News |access-date=July 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn May 30, 2019, Davies was named to the squad for the [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.canadasoccer.com/together-we-rise-canada-soccer-announces-squad-for-the-2019-concacaf-gold-cup-p162198 |title=Together We Rise: Canada Soccer announces squad for the 2019 Concacaf Gold Cup |date=May 30, 2019 |website=canadasoccer.com |access-date=June 25, 2019}}</ref> Davies was called up for a pair of [[2019\u201320 CONCACAF Nations League A]] matches against [[Cuba national football team|Cuba]] on September 7 and 10, 2019. In the second match, Davies scored the decisive goal in a 1\u20130 victory for Canada.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/alphonso-davies-scores-canada-beats-cuba-nations-league/ |title=Alphonso Davies scores as Canada beats Cuba in Nations League |date=September 10, 2019 |publisher=Sportsnet}}</ref> In October 2019, Davies would help lead Canada to their first win over the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] in 34 years, scoring the opening goal of their CONCACAF Nations League match, which ended 2\u20130.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theathletic.com/1297824/2019/10/16/canadas-historic-win-over-the-u-s-cements-alphonso-davies-as-the-face-of-the-program/ |title=Canada\u2019s historic win over the U.S. cements Alphonso Davies as the face of the program |last=Joshua Kloke |date=October 15, 2019 |website=The Athletic}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n{{updated|March 8, 2020|<ref name=\"Soccerway\" /><ref name=\"WorldFootball\" />}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|Cup{{efn|Includes [[Canadian Championship]] and [[DFB-Pokal]]}}\n!colspan=2|Continental\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[Whitecaps FC 2]]\n|[[2016 USL season|2016]]\n|[[USL Championship|USL]]\n|11||2||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||0||0||11||2\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Vancouver Whitecaps FC]]\n|[[2016 Vancouver Whitecaps FC season|2016]]\n|[[Major League Soccer|MLS]]\n|8||0||4||0||3{{efn|name=CCL|Appearance(s) in [[CONCACAF Champions League]]}}||1||colspan=2|\u2014||15||1\n|-\n|[[2017 Vancouver Whitecaps FC season|2017]]\n|MLS\n|26||0||2||2||4{{efn|name=CCL}}||1||1{{efn|Appearance(s) in [[MLS Cup Playoffs]]}}||0||33||3\n|-\n|[[2018 Vancouver Whitecaps FC season|2018]]\n|MLS\n|31||8||2||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||33||8\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total!!65!!8!!8!!2!!7!!2!!1!!0!!81!!12\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[FC Bayern Munich II|Bayern Munich II]]\n|[[2018\u201319 Regionalliga#Regionalliga Bayern|2018\u201319]]\n|[[Regionalliga Bayern]]\n|3||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||2{{efn|Appearance(s) in [[Promotion to the 3. Liga|3. Liga promotion play-offs]]}}||0||5||0\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 3. Liga|2019\u201320]]\n|[[3. Liga]]\n|3||0||0||0||0||0||0||0||3||0\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total!!6!!0!!0!!0!!0!!0!!2!!0!!8!!0\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]\n|[[2018\u201319 FC Bayern Munich season|2018\u201319]]\n|[[Bundesliga]]\n|6||1||0||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||6||1\n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 FC Bayern Munich season|2019\u201320]]\n|Bundesliga\n|21||1||3||0||4{{efn|name=UCL|Appearance(s) in [[UEFA Champions League]]}}||0||1{{efn|Appearance in [[DFL-Supercup]]}}||0||29||1\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total!!27!!2!!3!!0!!4!!0!!1!!0!!35!!2\n|-\n!colspan=3|Career total!!109!!12!!11!!2!!11!!2!!4!!0!!135!!16\n|}\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n===International===\n{{updated|November 15, 2019|<ref name=\"NFT profile\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.national-football-teams.com/player/68404/Alphonso_Davies.html |title=NFT profile |publisher=National Football Teams |access-date=July 12, 2017}}</ref>}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=3 | [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|2017||6||3\n|-\n|2018||3||0\n|-\n|2019||8||2\n|-\n!Total||17||5\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n{{updated|October 15, 2019|<ref name=\"NFT profile\" />}}\n{{hatnote|Scores and results list Canada's goal tally first.}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"style=font-size:95%;\"\n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1.\n| rowspan=\"2\"|July 7, 2017\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Red Bull Arena (New Jersey)|Red Bull Arena]], [[Harrison, New Jersey|Harrison]], United States\n| rowspan=\"2\"|{{fb|GYF|local}}\n| align=\"center\" | '''3'''\u20130\n| rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | 4\u20132\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup Group A|2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup]]\n|-\n| 2.\n| align=\"center\" | '''4'''\u20132\n|-\n| 3.\n| July 11, 2017\n| [[BBVA Compass Stadium]], [[Houston]], United States\n| {{fb|CRC}}\n| align=\"center\" | '''1'''\u20130\n| align=\"center\" | 1\u20131\n|-\n| 4.\n| September 10, 2019\n| [[Truman Bodden Sports Complex]], [[George Town, Cayman Islands|George Town]], Cayman Islands\n| {{fb|CUB}}\n| align=\"center\" | '''1'''\u20130\n| align=\"center\" | 1\u20130\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[2019\u201320 CONCACAF Nations League A]]\n|-\n| 5.\n| October 15, 2019\n| [[BMO Field]], [[Toronto]], Canada\n| {{fb|USA}}\n| align=\"center\" | '''1'''\u20130\n| align=\"center\" | 2\u20130\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''Bayern Munich'''\n* [[Bundesliga]]: [[2018\u201319 Bundesliga|2018\u201319]]\n* [[DFB-Pokal]]: [[2018\u201319 DFB-Pokal|2018\u201319]]\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Canadian U-17 Players of the Year|Canada U-17 Male Player of the Year]]: 2016,<ref name=\"U17 POTY 2016\" /> 2017<ref name=\"U17 POTY 2017\" />\n*[[CONCACAF Gold Cup]] Bright Future Award: [[2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2017]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.goldcup.org/en/young-player-award |title=Canada's Davies merits Young Player Award presented by Scotiabank |date=July 26, 2017 |website=goldcup.org |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170726092530/http://www.goldcup.org/en/young-player-award |archive-date=July 26, 2017 |access-date=July 27, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[CONCACAF Gold Cup]] Golden Boot Award: [[2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2017]]<ref name=\"CanadaSoccerGoldCup2017\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.canadasoccer.com/alphonso-davies-wins-young-player-golden-boot-and-best-xi-at-gold-cup-2017-p161038 |title=Alphonso Davies wins Young Player, Golden Boot and Best XI at Gold Cup 2017 |date=July 26, 2017 |website=canadasoccer.com |access-date=July 27, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[CONCACAF Gold Cup]] Best XI: [[2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2017]]<ref name=\"CanadaSoccerGoldCup2017\" />\n*[[Major League Soccer All-Star Game|MLS All-Star]]: [[2018 MLS All-Star Game|2018]]<ref name=\"All-Star\" />\n*[[Vancouver Whitecaps FC#Player of the year|Vancouver Whitecaps FC Player of the Year]]: [[2018 Vancouver Whitecaps FC season|2018]]<ref name=\"POTY\" />\n*[[Vancouver Whitecaps FC]] Goal of the Year: [[2018 Vancouver Whitecaps FC season|2018]]<ref name=\"POTY\" />\n*[[Canadian Players of the Year|Canadian Men's Player of the Year]]: 2018<ref>{{Cite news |last=Molinaro |first=John |url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/alphonso-davies-named-canadian-mens-player-year/ |title=Alphonso Davies named Canadian men's player of the year |date=December 12, 2018 |access-date=December 12, 2018 |publisher=[[Sportsnet]] |website=sportsnet.ca}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.whitecapsfc.com/players/alphonso-davies Alphonso Davies] at WhitecapsFC.com\n* {{NFT|68404}}\n\n{{FC Bayern Munich squad}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Canada squads\n|bg = red\n|fg = white\n|list1=\n{{Canada squad 2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n{{Canada squad 2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards\n| bg    = gold\n| fg    = navy\n| list1 =\n{{Canadian Player of the Year}}\n{{CONCACAF Gold Cup awards}}\n{{Canadian U-17 Players of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davies, Alphonso}}\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Liberian descent]]\n[[Category:People from Central Region (Ghana)]]\n[[Category:Black Canadian sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Soccer people from Alberta]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Edmonton]]\n[[Category:Liberian emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian soccer players]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Whitecaps FC 2 players]]\n[[Category:Vancouver Whitecaps FC players]]\n[[Category:FC Bayern Munich footballers]]\n[[Category:FC Bayern Munich II players]]\n[[Category:USL Championship players]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer players]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Regionalliga players]]\n[[Category:Canada men's youth international soccer players]]\n[[Category:Canada men's international soccer players]]\n[[Category:2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup players]]\n[[Category:2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup players]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate soccer players]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate sportspeople in Germany]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Canadian English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name                = Alphonso Davies\n|image               = 20190428 DFL 1. Bundesliga FCN - FCB DSC 7707.jpg\n|image_size          =\n|caption             = Davies playing for [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] in 2019\n|fullname            = Alphonso Boyle Davies\n|birth_date          = {{birth date and age|2000|11|2}}\n|birth_place         = [[Buduburam]], Ghana\n|height              = 1.81 m<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://fcbayern.com/en/teams/professionals/alphonso-davies |title=Alphonso Davies Bayern Munich Profile |access-date=October 19, 2019}}</ref>\n|position            = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]], [[Defender (association football)#Wing-back|wing-back]]\n|currentclub         = [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]\n|clubnumber          = 19\n|youthyears1         = {{0|0000}}\u20132005\n|youthclubs1         = Edmonton Internationals\n|youthyears2         = 2006\u20132014\n|youthclubs2         = Edmonton Strikers\n|youthyears3         = 2015\u20132016\n|youthclubs3         = [[Vancouver Whitecaps FC Academy|Whitecaps FC Residency]]\n|years1              = 2016\n|clubs1              = [[Whitecaps FC 2]]\n|caps1               = 11\n|goals1              = 2\n|years2              = 2016\u20132018\n|clubs2              = [[Vancouver Whitecaps FC]]\n|caps2               = 65\n|goals2              = 8\n|years3              = 2019\n|clubs3              = [[FC Bayern Munich II|Bayern Munich II]]\n|caps3               = 6\n|goals3              = 0\n|years4              = 2019\u2013\n|clubs4              = [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]]\n|caps4               = 27\n|goals4              = 2\n|nationalyears1      = 2016\n|nationalteam1       = [[Canada men's national under-17 soccer team|Canada U17]]\n|nationalcaps1       = 2\n|nationalgoals1      = 1\n|nationalyears2      = 2016\n|nationalteam2       = [[Canada men's national under-20 soccer team|Canada U20]]\n|nationalcaps2       = 1\n|nationalgoals2      = 0\n|nationalyears3      = 2017\u2013\n|nationalteam3       = [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]]\n|nationalcaps3       = 17\n|nationalgoals3      = 5\n|club-update         = 16:24, March 8, 2020 (UTC)\n|nationalteam-update = November 15, 2019\n}}\n\n'''Alphonso Boyle Davies''' (born November 2, 2000)<ref name=\"Canada Soccer profile\">{{Cite web |url=https://canadasoccer.com/index.php?pid=5810&t=profile |title=Alphonso Davies |publisher=Canada Soccer |access-date=March 11, 2018}}</ref> is a Canadian professional [[association football|soccer]]<!--Davies is a Canadian and the name of the sport in Canada is \"soccer\". MOS:TIES applies to the WP:LANGVAG used.--> player who plays as a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] and [[Left-Back|left back]] for [[Bundesliga]] club [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] and the [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada national team]]. He was the first player born in the 2000s to play in a [[Major League Soccer]] match. Davies joined Bayern in January 2019 from MLS side [[Vancouver Whitecaps FC]] on a contract lasting until 2023 for a then-MLS record transfer fee.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://fcbayern.com/de/news/2018/07/fc-bayern-verpflichtet-alphonso-davies-bis-2023 |title=FC Bayern verpflichtet Alphonso Davies bis 2023 |date=July 25, 2018 |access-date=July 25, 2018 |language=German |trans-title=Bayern commits Alphonso Davies until 2023 |website=FC Bayern Munich}}</ref><ref name=\"MLS record\" />\n\nIn June 2017, he became the youngest player to appear for the Canadian men's national team.<ref name=\"talent belies his youth\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/soccer/2017/07/05/canadian-soccer-phenom-alphonso-davies-talent-belies-his-youth.html |title=Canadian soccer phenom Alphonso Davies' talent belies his youth |last=Buhler |first=Andy |website=The Star |access-date=July 8, 2017}}</ref> By scoring two goals in a [[2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup]] match against [[French Guiana national football team|French Guiana]], he became the youngest player to score for the Canadian men's national team, the youngest to score at the [[CONCACAF Gold Cup]], and first player born in the 2000s to score at a top level international tournament.<ref name=\"becomes first\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/588/gold-cup/2017/07/07/36915632/davies-becomes-first-2000s-born-player-to-score-at-a-top |title=Davies becomes first 2000s-born player to score at a top level international tournament |last=Schuller |first=Rudi |publisher=Goal.com |access-date=July 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nDavies was born in [[Buduburam]], a refugee camp in the [[Gomoa East District]] of Ghana, to Liberian parents.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49841881 |title=Alphonso Davies: The Bayern Munich winger born in a refugee camp |date=September 26, 2019 |publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/alphonso-davies-canada-national-team-vancouver-whitecaps-mls-major-league-soccer/ |title=Whitecaps phenom Davies receives Canadian citizenship, 1st senior call-up |last=Asano |first=Naoko |website=Sportsnet |access-date=June 7, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Bayern Munich: Who is new signing Alphonso Davies?\">{{Cite news |last=Penfold |first=Chuck |url=https://www.dw.com/en/bayern-munich-who-is-new-signing-alphonso-davies/a-44824675 |title=Bayern Munich: Who is new signing Alphonso Davies? |date=July 26, 2018 |access-date=July 27, 2018 |publisher=Deutsche Welle}}</ref> His parents lived there after fleeing their homeland during the [[Second Liberian Civil War]], which displaced more than 450,000 people in [[Liberia]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://journals.lib.unb.ca/index.php/jcs/article/view/11734/12489 |title=The Civil War and the Refugee Crisis in Liberia |access-date=July 24, 2018}}</ref> When Davies was five, his family came to Canada as refugees, and moved to [[Windsor, Ontario]],<ref name=\"auto\" /><ref name=\"talent belies his youth\" /> before relocating a year later to [[Edmonton]].<ref name=\"talent belies his youth\" /><ref name=\"Bayern Munich: Who is new signing Alphonso Davies?\" /> On June 6, 2017, he officially received Canadian citizenship.<ref name=\"citizenship\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.whitecapsfc.com/post/2017/06/06/alphonso-davies-receives-canadian-citizenship-and-first-senior-call-canada |title=Alphonso Davies receives Canadian citizenship and first senior call-up to Canada |access-date=June 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Youth career===\nAfter playing for Edmonton Internationals, and Edmonton Strikers, Davies joined the [[Vancouver Whitecaps FC Residency|Whitecaps FC Residency]] in 2015 at the age of 14.<ref name=\"kicker profile\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/bundesliga/vereine/1-bundesliga/2018/bayern-muenchen-14/99583/spieler_alphonso-davies.html |title=Alphonso Davies |website=kicker.de |language=de |access-date=February 2, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.whitecapsfc.com/players/alphonso-davies |title=Whitecaps FC Profile: Alphonso Davies |access-date=February 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Whitecaps FC 2===\nAfter joining [[Vancouver Whitecaps FC]] during their 2016 MLS preseason tour,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theprovince.com/sports/Weber+Caps+give+youth+chance+year+Alphonso+Davies/11708472/story.html |title=Caps give youth a chance in 15-year-old Alphonso Davies |last=Weber |first=Marc |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531023646/http://www.theprovince.com/sports/weber+caps+give+youth+chance+year+alphonso+davies/11708472/story.html |archive-date=May 31, 2016 |access-date=February 24, 2016}}</ref> Davies signed with [[Whitecaps FC 2]] in the [[United Soccer League|USL]] on February 23, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.whitecapsfc.com/wfc2/post/2016/02/22/whitecaps-fc-sign-teenagers-matthew-baldisimo-and-alphonso-davies-wfc2 |title=Whitecaps FC sign teenagers Matthew Baldisimo and Alphonso Davies to WFC2 |access-date=February 24, 2016}}</ref> At the time of his signing, he became the youngest player signed to a USL contract at 15 years, 3 months. Davies made his professional debut for Whitecaps FC 2 at the age of 15 years, 5 months in April 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/wfc2/status/716433490217148416 |title=Whitecaps FC 2 on Twitter |access-date=July 17, 2016}}</ref> On May 15, 2016, he scored his first professional goal, making him the youngest goal scorer in USL history at 15 years, 6 months.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/USL/status/731961905821057024 |title=USL on Twitter |access-date=July 17, 2016}}</ref> He scored two goals in 11 games played during the [[2016 USL season|2016 season]].<ref name=\"Soccerway\">{{Cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/alphonso-davies/441396/ |title=Alphonso Davies profile |website=Soccerway}}</ref>\n\n===Vancouver Whitecaps FC===\nDavies was named to the Whitecaps roster for the [[2016 Canadian Championship]] on a short term contract.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.whitecapsfc.com/post/2016/05/31/whitecaps-fc-submit-20-man-roster-acc |title=Whitecaps FC submit 20-man roster in advance of Wednesday's Amway Canadian Championship semifinal &#124; Vancouver Whitecaps FC}}</ref> On June 1, 2016, he made his first team debut in the first leg of the Canadian Championship against the [[Ottawa Fury]] and started the second leg in Vancouver.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/WhitecapsFC/status/738176377921249281 |title=Vancouver Whitecaps on Twitter |access-date=July 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn July 15, 2016, Davies signed a first team contract with the Whitecaps through 2018, with options for the 2019 and 2020 seasons. At the time of his signing, he was the youngest active player in [[Major League Soccer]], and the third youngest player to have signed an MLS contract.<ref name=\"fifteen\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.whitecapsfc.com/post/2016/07/15/whitecaps-fc-add-15-year-old-residency-product-alphonso-davies |title=Whitecaps FC add 15-year-old Residency product Alphonso Davies to MLS roster |date=July 15, 2016 |publisher=Vancouver Whitecaps FC}}</ref> Davies made his MLS debut on July 16, 2016, becoming the second youngest player to play in MLS, behind [[Freddy Adu]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/youngster-alphonso-davies-impresses-mls-debut-whitecaps/ |title=Youngster Alphonso Davies impresses in MLS debut for Whitecaps |date=July 16, 2016 |publisher=Sportsnet}}</ref> In September 2016, he scored his first goal for the first team in the [[2016\u201317 CONCACAF Champions League]] against [[Sporting Kansas City]] in injury time to send the club through to the knockout round.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/WhitecapsFC/status/775908017636253696 |title=SCCL quarterfinal berth: CLINCHED!!! |date=September 13, 2016 |publisher=Vancouver Whitecaps FC Official Twitter}}</ref> In September 2016, Davies became the second youngest starter in MLS history when he started a game against the [[Colorado Rapids]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2016/09/24/whitecaps-alphonso-davies-15-second-youngest-starter-mls-history |title=Whitecaps' Alphonso Davies, 15, is second-youngest starter in MLS history |last=Stephen |first=Colin |date=September 24, 2016 |publisher=MLS Official Website}}</ref> On October, 2, 2016 he started against rival club [[Seattle Sounders FC]] earning a penalty kick.<ref name=\"Vancouver Whitecaps 1, Seattle Sounders 2\">{{Cite web |url=https://matchcenter.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter/2016-10-02-vancouver-whitecaps-fc-vs-seattle-sounders-fc/recap |title=Vancouver Whitecaps 1, Seattle Sounders 2 |last=Boehm |first=Charles |publisher=Major League Soccer |access-date=July 8, 2017}}</ref> During the [[2016 Vancouver Whitecaps FC season|2016 season]], Davies played in eight MLS games,<ref name=\"WorldFootball\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/alphonso-davies/2/ |title=Alphonso Davies \u00bb Club matches |publisher=World Football |access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref> four Canadian Championship games,<ref name=\"WorldFootball\" /> and three games in the CONCACAF Champions League.<ref name=\"Alphonso Davies \u00bb CONCACAF Champions League 2016/2017\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/alphonso-davies/concacaf-champions-league-2016-2017/vancouver-whitecaps/3/ |title=Alphonso Davies \u00bb CONCACAF Champions League 2016/2017 |publisher=World Football |access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his impressive early MLS appearances, Davies attracted interest and was scouted by European clubs including [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], and [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]],<ref name=\"Giants\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.metro.us/sports/source-alphonso-davies-being-trailed-by-three-english-premier-league-giants/zsJqci---b4pyPX6iT1FuM |title=Source: Alphonso Davies being trailed by three English Premier League giants |last=Dyer |first=Kristian |publisher=Metro.us |access-date=July 9, 2017}}</ref> and was also named one of the 60 best young soccer talents in the world in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/ng-interactive/2017/oct/04/next-generation-2017-60-of-the-best-young-talents-in-world-football |title=Next Generation 2017: 60 of the best young talents in world football |website=The Guardian |access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2018 Vancouver Whitecaps FC season|2018 season]] opener against the [[Montreal Impact]], Davies scored his first goal in MLS action, and assisted on a [[Kei Kamara]] goal.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://matchcenter.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter/2018-03-04-vancouver-whitecaps-fc-vs-montreal-impact/recap |title=Recap: Vancouver Whitecaps FC vs. Montreal Impact |last=Boehm |first=Charles |date=March 4, 2018 |website=MLS}}</ref> On June 10, 2018, he scored a goal and got three assists in a 5\u20132 win over [[Orlando City SC|Orlando City]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/soccer/article-alphonso-davies-has-goal-three-assists-to-lead-whitecaps-past-orlando/ |title=Alphonso Davies has goal, three assists to lead Whitecaps past Orlando City |last=Dyck |first=Darryl |date=June 10, 2018 |website=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> Davies scored two goals and provided two assists to help his side defeat [[Minnesota United FC (2010\u201316)|Minnesota United]] with a 4\u20132 victory on July 29.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2018/07/29/bayern-munich-bound-alphonso-davies-destroys-loons-whitecaps-win |title=Bayern Munich-bound Alphonso Davies destroys Loons as Whitecaps win |publisher=Major League Soccer |access-date=July 29, 2018}}</ref> On June 29, 2018, Davies was included in the MLS All-Star roster for the [[2018 MLS All-Star Game]] on August 1 against [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]].<ref name=\"All-Star\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/all-star/2018/rosters/mls-all-star-team |title=2018 MLS All-Star Roster |date=June 29, 2018 |website=MLSsoccer.com |publisher=[[Major League Soccer]] |access-date=June 16, 2018}}</ref> Davies made an appearance during the match, which finished as a 3\u20135 penalty shoot-out loss following a 1\u20131 draw.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Roberson |first=Doug |url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/martinez-mls-all-stars-tie-juventus-front-record-crowd/7xztCXmW1mO712v99nD8NL/ |title=Martinez scores but MLS All-Stars fall to Juventus in front of record crowd |date=August 1, 2018 |access-date=August 1, 2018 |publisher=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] |website=AJC.com}}</ref> Davies was named the Vancouver Whitecaps FC Player of the Year on October 24,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Adams |first=J.J. |url=https://theprovince.com/sports/soccer/mls/vancouver-whitecaps/alphonso-davies-named-whitecaps-player-of-the-year |title=Alphonso Davies named Caps' player of the year |date=October 24, 2018 |work=[[The Province]] |access-date=October 30, 2018}}</ref> and also received the Whitecaps' Goal of the Year award.<ref name=\"POTY\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.whitecapsfc.com/post/2018/10/24/winners-announced-2018-whitecaps-fc-player-awards-presented-bmo |title=Winners announced for 2018 Whitecaps FC Player Awards, presented by BMO |date=October 24, 2018 |access-date=October 30, 2018 |publisher=[[Vancouver Whitecaps FC]] |website=whitecapsfc.com}}</ref> In Davies' final game for Vancouver on October 28, he scored both goals in a 2\u20131 victory over the Portland Timbers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4605129/alphonso-davies-final-vancouver-game/ |title=Emotional sendoff as Alphonso Davies plays final game as Vancouver Whitecap |last=Little |first=Simon |date=October 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Bayern Munich===\n\nOn July 25, 2018, Vancouver announced that it had agreed to a multi-million-dollar transfer of Davies to [[Bundesliga]] club [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]], with Davies seeing out the 2018 MLS season with Vancouver, before joining Bayern in January 2019.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44964070 |title=Alphonso Davies: Bayern Munich sign 17-year-old for MLS record fee |date=July 26, 2018 |publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.whitecapsfc.com/post/2018/07/25/whitecaps-fc-agree-mls-record-breaking-transfer-homegrown-midfielder-alphonso-davies |title=Whitecaps FC agree to MLS record-breaking transfer of Homegrown midfielder Alphonso Davies to Germany's most storied club FC Bayern Munich |date=July 25, 2018 |publisher=Vancouver Whitecaps FC |access-date=July 25, 2018}}</ref> The base fee for the transfer is US$13.5&nbsp;million, with performance-related bonuses that total $22&nbsp;million, a then-record for MLS,<ref name=\"MLS record\">{{Cite news |last=Lindberg |first=Austin |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/soccer-transfers/story/3573807/bayern-munich-sign-canadian-teen-alphonso-davies-in-mls-record-deal |title=Bayern Munich sign Canadian teen Alphonso Davies in MLS-record deal |date=July 25, 2018 |access-date=July 25, 2018 |publisher=ESPN}}</ref> later eclipsed by the transfer of [[Miguel Almiron]] to [[Newcastle United]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2019/01/31/miguel-almiron-completes-record-transfer-atlanta-newcastle |title=Miguel Almiron completes record transfer from Atlanta to Newcastle |date=January 31, 2019 |publisher=MLS Soccer |access-date=January 31, 2019}}</ref> Davies had his first training session with Bayern on November 21, 2018,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/bayern-munich/story/3705715/canadas-alphonso-davies-very-excited-as-bayern-munich-career-begins |title=Canada's Alphonso Davies 'very excited' as Bayern Munich career begins |last=Uersfeld |first=Stephan |date=November 22, 2018 |publisher=ESPN |access-date=November 22, 2018}}</ref> and debuted on January 12, 2019 against [[Borussia M\u00f6nchengladbach]] in the [[Telekom Cup]] championship finale, which Bayern won on penalties following a scoreless draw.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.whitecapsfc.com/post/2019/01/13/alphonso-davies-shows-attacking-flair-bayern-munich-debut |title=Alphonso Davies shows attacking flair in Bayern Munich debut |last=Devji |first=Farhan |date=January 13, 2019 |access-date=January 19, 2019}}</ref> Davies made his Bundesliga debut on January 27 against [[VfB Stuttgart]], appearing as a late substitute for [[Kingsley Coman]] in a 3\u20131 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/alphonso-davies-bundesliga-debut-bayern-1.4995003 |title=Alphonso Davies makes league debut for Bayern Munich in win |date=January 27, 2019 |access-date=February 1, 2019}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Bayern on March 17, netting the final goal in a 6\u20130 rout of [[1. FSV Mainz 05|Mainz 05]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2019/03/17/alphonso-davies-bayern-munich-first-goal-watch-mainz |title=Alphonso Davies Scores First Ever Goal for Bayern Munich in Huge Win Over Mainz |last=Echegaray |first=Luis Miguel |date=March 17, 2019 |website=Sports Illustrated |access-date=March 17, 2019}}</ref> In doing so, and at the age of 18 years, 4 months and 15 days, he became the youngest player since [[Roque Santa Cruz]], twenty years prior, to score for the club. He is the first Canadian international to score for Bayern.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/bayern-munich-mainz-live-line-ups-stats-thomas-muller-james-rodriguez-hummels-3035 |title=James Rodriguez hat-trick and maiden Alphonso Davies goal send Bayern Munich top after crushing Mainz win |date=March 17, 2019 |access-date=March 18, 2019 |publisher=Bundesliga}}</ref> On May 18, 2019, Davies won his first Bundesliga title as Bayern finished two points above [[Borussia Dortmund|Dortmund]] with 78 points. A week later, Davies won his first [[DFB-Pokal]] as Bayern defeated [[RB Leipzig]] 3\u20130 in the [[2019 DFB-Pokal Final]]. Davies was not selected for the match day squad.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/rb-leipzig-bayern-munich-live-dfb-cup-final-james-rodriguez-lewandowski-neuer-4678 |title=Robert Lewandowski hits brace as Bayern Munich beat RB Leipzig in DFB Cup final to seal the double |publisher=bundesliga.com |access-date=May 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDavies made his first Bundesliga start with Bayern on matchday nine of the [[2019\u201320 Bundesliga]] season, going the full 90 minutes in a 2\u20131 home victory over [[1. FC Union Berlin|Union Berlin]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/alphonso-davies-inspired-by-robert-lewandowski-bayern-munich-7771 |title=Davies lauds Lewandowki |website=bundesliga.com |access-date=October 28, 2019}}</ref> He made his first [[UEFA Champions League]] start on November 6, 2019, in a 2\u20130 victory against [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/bayern-munich-olympiacos-champions-league-live-line-ups-stats-lewandowski-7935 |title=Robert Lewandowski on target again as Bayern Munich down Olympiacos to reach UEFA Champions League last 16 |date=November 6, 2019 |website=bundesliga.com |access-date=November 6, 2019}}</ref> Throughout the 2019\u201320 season, Davies would play as a left back to allow [[David Alaba]] to play at centre back. Davies would earn high praise during his time in that role, being considered one of the best left backs in the world.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/alphonso-davies-is-the-bayern-munich-teen-one-of-the-world-s-best-left-backs-9896 |title=Alphonso Davies: Is the Bayern Munich teenager one of the best left-backs in the world? |date=February 22, 2020 |website=Bundesliga}}</ref>{{better source|reason=the Bundesliga is the league Davies plays in, and therefore has a conflict of interest to make him look good|date=February 2020}} On February 25, 2020, Davies set-up [[Robert Lewandowski]]'s goal in a 3\u20130 away win over [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in the first leg of the round of 16 of the [[2019\u201320 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|UEFA Champions League]]; his performance during the match was widely praised in the media, with pundit [[Gary Lineker]] commenting that Davies played \"beautifully,\" while former U.S. international [[Stuart Holden]] described him as a \"world class left back.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6595963/alphonso-davies-bayern-munich-chelsea-champions-league/ |title=Alphonso Davies shines in Bayern Munich\u2019s 3-0 Champions League win at Chelsea |work=Global News |date=February 25, 2020 |accessdate=March 19, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Alphonso_Davies_2018.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Davies with Canada during a match against [[Dominica national football team|Dominica]] at [[BMO Field]] in [[Toronto]], October 16, 2018]]\n===Youth teams===\nAlthough a Liberian citizen by birth, Davies was called to numerous Canadian U-15 and U-18 camps in 2014 and 2015.<ref name=\"Canada Soccer profile\" /> On March 17, 2016, he was called up to the Canada U20 squad for a friendly against England U20.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://canadasoccer.com/canada-soccer-selects-players-for-england-youth-friendly-p159270 |title=Canada Soccer selects players for England youth friendly |publisher=Canada Soccer |access-date=July 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/alphonso-davies-soccer-1.3494605 |title=Alphonso Davies joins Canada's U-20 soccer team |access-date=March 27, 2016}}</ref> In November 2016, Davies attended a Canadian U-17 camp, where he scored against [[Jamaica national under-17 football team|Jamaica]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theprovince.com/sports/alphonso+davies+scores+canadas+under17+squad+friendly+over+jamaica/12441846/story.html |title=Alphonso Davies scores for Canada's under-17 squad in friendly win over Jamaica |date=November 26, 2016 |publisher=Vancouver Province |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129144149/http://www.theprovince.com/sports/alphonso+davies+scores+canadas+under17+squad+friendly+over+jamaica/12441846/story.html |archive-date=November 29, 2016 |access-date=November 29, 2016 |agency=The Canadian Press}}</ref> In 2016, he was named the Canada U17 Male Player of the Year for his performances with the U-17 and U-20 squads in friendlies.<ref name=\"U17 POTY 2016\">{{Cite web |url=http://canadasoccer.com/davies-and-rose-win-2016-canadian-u-17-players-of-the-year-p160230 |title=Davies and Rose win 2016 Canadian U-17 Players of the Year |date=December 13, 2016 |publisher=Canada Soccer}}</ref> In March 2017, Davies stated in an interview that, \"to be able to represent Canada, it is one of my dreams.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theprovince.com/sports/soccer/mls/vancouver-whitecaps/his-talent-was-evident-whitecaps-teenage-soccer-phenom-turning-heads |title='His talent was evident': Alphonso Davies is dropping jaws, one at a time |date=March 30, 2017 |website=Vancouver Province}}</ref> In 2017, he was named the Canada U17 Male Player of the Year for a second time due to his performances with the senior team.<ref name=\"U17 POTY 2017\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.canadasoccer.com/davies-huitema-named-canadian-u-17-players-of-the-year-for-canada-soccer-p161311-preview-1 |title=Davies & Huitema named Canadian U-17 Players of the Year for Canada Soccer |date=December 11, 2017 |website=Canada Soccer}}</ref>\n\n===Senior team===\nOn June 6, 2017, Davies passed his citizenship test and officially became a citizen of Canada, making him eligible to play for the [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada national team]].<ref name=\"citizenship\" /> On the same day, Davies was added to a senior team camp for a friendly against [[Cura\u00e7ao national football team|Cura\u00e7ao]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Clipperton |first=Joshua |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/mls/alphonso-davies-receives-canadian-citizenship-first-national-team-call-up-1.4148883 |title=Teen's soccer journey takes him from refugee camp to Canada's national team |date=June 6, 2017 |access-date=October 30, 2018 |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |agency=[[The Canadian Press]]}}</ref> as well as Canada's preliminary 40-man roster for the [[2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2017 Gold Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://canadasoccer.com/canada-soccer-releases-40-man-provisional-list-for-concacaf-gold-cup-p160880 |title=Canada Soccer releases 40-man Provisional List for CONCACAF Gold Cup |date=June 6, 2017 |website=Canada Soccer}}</ref> Davies would debut for the senior team in the friendly against Cura\u00e7ao at the age of 16, making him the youngest player to play for the national team.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Heidenreich |first=Phil |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/3526091/teen-soccer-star-from-edmonton-impresses-in-history-making-debut-for-team-canada/ |title=Teen soccer star from Edmonton impresses in history making debut for Team Canada |date=June 14, 2017 |access-date=October 30, 2018 |publisher=[[Global News]] |website=globalnews.ca}}</ref> On June 27, Davies was named to the final 23-man squad for the [[2017 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2017 Gold Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/06/27/canada-names-nine-mls-players-23-man-concacaf-gold-cup-roster |title=Canada names nine MLS players to 23-man CONCACAF Gold Cup roster |last=Zeitlin |first=Dave |date=June 27, 2017}}</ref> In Canada's first match of that tournament, Davies scored twice in a 4\u20132 victory over [[French Guiana national football team|French Guiana]]. The goals make him the youngest goalscorer in Gold Cup history.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/canada-french-guiana-gold-cup-recap-1.4195412 |title=Teen Alphonso Davies scores 2 in Canada's Gold Cup win |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |access-date=July 8, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/canada-french-guiana-concacaf-gold-cup-alphonso-davies-octavio-zambrano/ |title=Canada walks away with win and lessons learned in Gold Cup opener |website=Sportsnet.ca |access-date=July 8, 2017}}</ref> He then scored in their second match against [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]] to earn a 1\u20131 draw.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.canadasoccer.com/canada-stays-atop-group-a-with-impressive-1-1-draw-with-costa-rica-at-concacaf-gold-cup-p161011 |title=Canada stays atop Group A with impressive 1:1 draw with Costa Rica at CONCACAF Gold Cup |website=canadasoccer.com}}</ref> Davies went on to win the Golden Boot as the tournament's top scorer, the Young Player of the Tournament award, and was included in the tournament's Best XI selection.<ref name=\"trio of Gold Cup awards\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/ca/soccer/news/gold-cup-2017-canadas-davies-named-best-young-player/wqonov7ykcdy1aa7d63qc2xn0 |title=Canada's Alphonso Davies wins trio of Gold Cup awards |last=Schuller |first=Rudi |publisher=Sporting News |access-date=July 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn May 30, 2019, Davies was named to the squad for the [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.canadasoccer.com/together-we-rise-canada-soccer-announces-squad-for-the-2019-concacaf-gold-cup-p162198 |title=Together We Rise: Canada Soccer announces squad for the 2019 Concacaf Gold Cup |date=May 30, 2019 |website=canadasoccer.com |access-date=June 25, 2019}}</ref> Davies was called up for a pair of [[2019\u201320 CONCACAF Nations League A]] matches against [[Cuba national football team|Cuba]] on September 7 and 10, 2019. In the second match, Davies scored the decisive goal in a 1\u20130 victory for Canada.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/alphonso-davies-scores-canada-beats-cuba-nations-league/ |title=Alphonso Davies scores as Canada beats Cuba in Nations League |date=September 10, 2019 |publisher=Sportsnet}}</ref> In October 2019, Davies would help lead Canada to their first win over the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] in 34 years, scoring the opening goal of their CONCACAF Nations League match, which ended 2\u20130.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://theathletic.com/1297824/2019/10/16/canadas-historic-win-over-the-u-s-cements-alphonso-davies-as-the-face-of-the-program/ |title=Canada\u2019s historic win over the U.S. cements Alphonso Davies as the face of the program |last=Joshua Kloke |date=October 15, 2019 |website=The Athletic}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n{{updated|March 8, 2020|<ref name=\"Soccerway\" /><ref name=\"WorldFootball\" />}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|Cup{{efn|Includes [[Canadian Championship]] and [[DFB-Pokal]]}}\n!colspan=2|Continental\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|[[Whitecaps FC 2]]\n|[[2016 USL season|2016]]\n|[[USL Championship|USL]]\n|11||2||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||0||0||11||2\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Vancouver Whitecaps FC]]\n|[[2016 Vancouver Whitecaps FC season|2016]]\n|[[Major League Soccer|MLS]]\n|8||0||4||0||3{{efn|name=CCL|Appearance(s) in [[CONCACAF Champions League]]}}||1||colspan=2|\u2014||15||1\n|-\n|[[2017 Vancouver Whitecaps FC season|2017]]\n|MLS\n|26||0||2||2||4{{efn|name=CCL}}||1||1{{efn|Appearance(s) in [[MLS Cup Playoffs]]}}||0||33||3\n|-\n|[[2018 Vancouver Whitecaps FC season|2018]]\n|MLS\n|31||8||2||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||33||8\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total!!65!!8!!8!!2!!7!!2!!1!!0!!81!!12\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[FC Bayern Munich II|Bayern Munich II]]\n|[[2018\u201319 Regionalliga#Regionalliga Bayern|2018\u201319]]\n|[[Regionalliga Bayern]]\n|3||0||colspan=2|\u2014||colspan=2|\u2014||2{{efn|Appearance(s) in [[Promotion to the 3. Liga|3. Liga promotion play-